snippet.title: Paris 12th Arrondissement - 20 in 20 Day 12 - Rue Cremieux and Coulee Verte
snippet.description:
Paris' 12th arrondissement isn't one I'd go to for coffee or a meal, but it does have Rue Cremieux and the Coulee Verte, which are both fantastic spots to wander and take photos. Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide for these and plenty of other options for food, drinks, and coffee while visiting the 12th and surrounding areas!

Help me make better videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:

More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Follow Kate from Dear Everest here: http://instagram.com/deareverest

Music by: David Cutter Music - http://www.davidcuttermusic.co.uk

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

comments.textDisplay:
If Jay will permit me a few extra details!
Inside the lovely Gare de Lyon is the Galérie des Fresques (the Fresco Gallery) which contains some stunning paintings of the destinations served from the train station. The Gare de Lyon was the Paris terminus of the Paris, Lyon, Mediterranean railway (before nationalisation) - you get the picture - some of most glorious railway destinations in France wonderfully illustrated on the walls of the Galérie - well worth popping in.

Bang opposite the station is the restaurant L'Européen with its hall of mirrors interior somewhere between Art Nouveau and Art Déco - it's quite the Parisian dining experience especially if you like seafood (try the oysters).

comments.textDisplay: When you were on top of the old train station line (?) the trees were blowing and it felt like you would get a cooling rain... (that's what it does here right before it rains).  I love that I could see the tops of the buildings (so beautiful!), some with enviable terraces, ooh la la sighhh.  Liked the shops underneath the arches beneath also.  I am still fascinated by the "Wallace fountains" you mentioned before in another arrondissement, how would I have ever found out about that without your vlog?  Reading outside in a beautiful spot, priceless- in Paris, triple priceless :)  I will not be surprised a bit to find out someday that you own the top floor of beautiful buildings in Paris.  Like everyone that lands here, I am loving this 20/20 series, Merci beaucoup!

comments.textDisplay: Where's Bercy?! The big park has a rose garden, ponds with ducks, sculpture, etc., plus Cour Saint-Emilion, Bercy Village shopping & cinema, market and the stadium with grass lawns planted diagonally. It's easy to reach on the new #14 purple line, with driverless trains and nice new stations all with elevators &  escalators. Views of the national library and the Seine, but since it's all been redeveloped in the last 25 years it's a little less cramped and crumbling than other parts of Paris. 👍

replies.textDisplay: +Hazel Hoyte I just looked it up for you. The only umbrella restoration left in all of Europe is in the 3 rd district (3 ème arrondissement) of Paris. There might be some other restoration shops that also restore antique umbrellas. I don't mean to insult nor discourage anyone who is working on this craft. By all means, please do your best to save these beautiful objects! Here is the link to the one professional shop I am aware of http://parasolerieheurtault.com/michel-heurtault-2/ Top right, click on English if you need it.

There are coffee places and food everywhere. I'll admit that they are French coffee's though and not American style (which I see him have frequently). There are also artist atteliers for art restoration, book restoration, ceramics, all along Daumesnil. If he had come down the stairs at rue Montgallet, he would have found a coffee and bagel place :), another one at Croizer...maybe next time!
